                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/97: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-24T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 24, 1929—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 1:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>620. Following from American Consul at Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“July 23, 3 p.m. Ministry of Foreign Affairs today informed me that
                            China’s reply to Soviet Government’s second note is now being prepared,
                            that the date of its despatch is uncertain as yet, and that its tone
                            will be ‘peaceful’. I am reliably informed that a council of the
                            Ministry of Foreign Affairs in discussing the note yesterday
                            characterized it as ‘conciliatory’.</p>
                        <p>So far as I can judge, the officials of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
                            now appear to be less anxious over the Chinese Eastern Railway situation
                            than they were before Wang’s arrival in Nanking.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
